Introduction

A breif data analysis was conducted for a final term project for the course: Stats 128 An introductory course to statistical computing utilizing R, in which basic methods where shown to manipulate data and solve a range problems. Multiple packages such as RSQLite, ggplot2, and dplyr where used to facilitate the analysis. The answers to the the following questions where left to the unique interpretation of each student.

  1. Calculate the average of the course grades assigned.

  2. Are there any courses, sections or subjects that stand out as having the lowest average gpa or the highest average gpa?

  3. Do the grades given by individual instructors seem to stay the same over time or do they have any type of trend over time? If there is a trend, is it consistent across instructors or does in vary among instructors?

  4. Which 5 subject areas had the most professors in 2017? Pick a subject area with many professors. Scrape data on the professors ratings from ratemyprofessor.com and determine if these ratings have any correlation with the overall average gpa assigned by the professor over a reasonable time period.

  5. Construct an interesting data visualization from this dataset. What interesting finding emerges from your graph?

Packages Used

1)

The course grades where calculating by using the following formula: 4.0 * a_count + 3.5 * ab_count + 3.0 * b_count + 2.5 * bc_count + 2 * c_count + 1 * d_count) / (a_count + ab_count + b_count + bc_count + c_count + d_count + f_count. Non-letter grades such as nr and cr where discarded. Only A - F letter grades where taken into consideration.

Note: The total number of grades given is calculated and added to the data frame by using the following formula: (a_count + ab_count + b_count + bc_count + c_count + d_count + f_count)

grade_distributions = mutate(grade_distributions, average = ((4.0 * a_count + 3.5 * ab_count + 3.0 * b_count + 2.5 * bc_count + 2 * c_count + 1 * d_count) / (a_count + ab_count + b_count + bc_count + c_count + d_count + f_count)), TotGradGiven = (a_count + ab_count + b_count + bc_count + c_count + d_count + f_count))

head(grade_distributions$average)

2)

Many of the grades averages over 3.8 correspond to indepedent study courses or seminars which hurt the overall quality of analysis for this specific problem. Despite the issue mentioned above Air Force Aerospace Studies, African Languages, Literature, Art, and General Business where amongst the subjects with the highest GPA.

Note: Clearing the data set from all semiars and independent study courses may improve the ability to further analyze this specific question.

3)

Three professors that had a decent amount of time in the university where chosen in order to observe grade trends relevent to the extend of time professors teach. Eugenia, a Trigonometry professor, number displays that there is a drop over time if you compare 2014 Fall vs.2017 Fall grades. Check the graph out for your self. Marcus, a professor Neuroscience professor, does display another trend that can be further analyzed. Do students average better grades in the Fall, then they do in the Spring? Marcuss graph displayed a slight visual difference between the average grades of classes taught in the Fall vs.Spring.

4)

Courses that had the most professors where Spanish at 74, Math at 66, Psychology at 65, English at 62, Music at 57, and History at 43. The topic Math was chosen to pick two professors. A professor with a GPA averge under 2.5 and the other with an average of over 3.5. Professors Thomas E. overall quality scores were for the most part 1 and the level of difficulty alternated between 4 and 5. His average GPA was 2.481. Professor Daniel E. had a very good overall quality scores all 5s. His level of difficulty score varied from 5 to 2. His average GPA was 3.69. Rate my professor confirmed the correlation with the overall average.

Conclusion

While its a very superficial analysis, further action can be taken to completly analyze the data and come into a concrete answer. It can be seen that there is a slight GPA drop over the years shown in Eugenias graph but in order to fully come into a conclusion more professors have to be analyzed individually. A very critical finding was initiated by the observation made through Marcuss visual graph. Do students perform better during the Fall semester? This led me to further analyze individual subjects by term. It can be seen that GPA is significantly greater during the Fall, for each of those subjects chosen. If you dont ever want to worry about any of this I recommmend choosing Music as your major. It seems Music has the best GPA in the game. Well, atleast at UW Madison for the year 2017.
